🔹Step 1: Login to Oracle Container Registry
    Oracle requires license acceptance.
    Go to: https://container-registry.oracle.com
    Sign in with your Oracle account
    Navigate to database > free
    Click "Accept License Agreement"

🔹Step 2: Pull the Oracle 23ai Image    
    docker login container-registry.oracle.com
    # Enter Oracle username/password
    docker pull container-registry.oracle.com/database/free:latest

🔹Step 3: Run the Container with Persistent Volume
    Create a persistent volume for the database files:
      docker volume create oracle26ai-data

🔹Step 4:
    Now run the container:
    docker run -d --name oracle26ai -p 1521:1521 -p 5500:5500 -e ORACLE_PWD=oracle -v oracle26ai-data:/opt/oracle/oradata container-registry.oracle.com/database/free:latest

📌 Breakdown:
    1521: Oracle Listener port
    5500: Oracle Enterprise Manager Express (web UI)
    ORACLE_PWD: SYS and SYSTEM password
    oracle23ai-data: named Docker volume to persist database

🔹Step 4: Wait for Initialization:
    Check logs:
    docker logs -f oracle23ai

    Wait until you see:
        DATABASE IS READY TO USE!

🔹Step 5: Connect to Oracle
    Using sqlcl or sqlplus or VSCode extension or SQL Developer
    sqlplus system/oracle@localhost:1521/FREEPDB1
    sql system/oracle@localhost:1521/FREEPDB1

🔹Step 6: To login into the container
    docker exec -it oracle23ai bash
    
✅ Managing the Container
    | Action     | Command                           |
    | ---------- | --------------------------------- |
    | Stop       |  docker stop oracle23ai           |
    | Start      |  docker start oracle23ai          |
    | Remove     |  docker rm -f oracle23ai          |
    | View Logs  |  docker logs -f oracle23ai        |
    | Shell into |  docker exec -it oracle23ai bash  |
    | delete vol |  docker volume rm oracle23ai-data |
    | list vols  |  docker volume ls                 |
    | status     |  docker ps -a                     |

🧠 Notes
    1. Your data is safe as long as the oracle23ai-data volume exists.
    2. Use docker volume inspect oracle23ai-data to see where it is stored.

🟢Running docker stop oracle23ai will NOT remove the container or image.
   It only pauses the container (like shutting down a computer), and you 
   can start it again anytime without re-downloading or reconfiguring anything.
   
   docker stop oracle23ai.
   docker start oracle23ai
  
🟢To remove the container
    docker rm -f oracle23ai
    This will stop the container and remove it, but your data in the volume 
    will remain intact.  

🔴DO NOT use docker run again — unless:
    You deleted the container (with docker rm oracle23ai)
    You want to recreate it from scratch

    Otherwise, running docker run again with the same name (oracle23ai) will 
    give you an error like:
      docker: Error response from daemon: Conflict. The container name "/oracle23ai" 
      is already in use.
      You have to remove the old container first with docker rm -f oracle23ai.

✅ Importing datapump files to the Oracle Container:
      
    🔹Step 1: Copy the .dmp file to the host machine
        🔹Login into the Oracle container: docker exec -it oracle23ai bash

        🔹Create a directory to hold the dump file:
            mkdir -p /opt/oracle/admin/FREEPDB1/dpdump

        🔹Exit the container: exit

        🔹Copy the .dmp file from the host machine to the container:
            docker cp C:\Users\sabya\gitrepos\non-git\data\21c_data\f1data.dmp oracle23ai:/opt/oracle/admin/FREE/dpdump/
    
    🔹Step 2: Create Oracle directory:

        🔹Login to the Oracle container:
            docker exec -it oracle23ai bash

        🔹Login to sqlplus 
            sqlplus system/oracle@localhost:1521/FREEPDB1

        🔹Create a directory object for the dump file:
            CREATE OR REPLACE DIRECTORY dpdump AS '/opt/oracle/admin/FREE/dpdump';
            GRANT READ, WRITE ON DIRECTORY dpdump TO system;

        🔹Issue import command from the container:
            impdp system/oracle@FREEPDB1 \
                  DIRECTORY=dpdump \
                  DUMPFILE=f1data.dmp \
                  LOGFILE=import.log










